TUESDAY, AUGUST 2  

9:00 - 10:30  Second Keynote - Learning from the Present - Things that 
IP Got Right and  ATM got Wrong                        
    Van Jacobson, Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory   

"We can never get rid of mouse ideas completely; they keep turning
up again and again, and nibble, nibble - - no matter how often
we drive them off.  The best way to keep them down is to have a few
good strong cat ideas to chase them.  - Samuel Butler"            

Some researchers feel ATM is the future of networking.  Others see it
as CCITT's attempt to adapt X.25 to space-division switch fabrics.
Whichever view turns out to be correct, it is clear that ATM violates
many of the architectural principles that have made IP and the IP
Internet the world's largest, most successful data network.  Most
of these principles have to do with the ability of the architecture 
to scale and evolve - - areas where design mistakes are especially 
damning since the errors are invisible until the system has become 
large and expensive or impossible to fundamentally change.  In a 
feeble attempt to avert, or at least presage, some costly disasters, 
this talk will try to stir up a chase between some of the "cat ideas" 
in IP and the "mouse ideas" of ATM. 

Van Jacobson is a staff scientist at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
He has been there sine 1972.  Most of his time is spent reading email 
& trying to keep his cat entertained.  It has been years since he did
anything useful. 

